rk-takai-dead.html|accessdate=July 24, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=July 20, 2016}}</ref>\n|children    = 2<ref name=nyt/>\n|residence   = [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]], Hawaii, U.S.\n|alma_mater  = [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]]\n|profession  = \n|religion    = [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publicpolicy.billingschamber.com/voter-resources/official/193955/K.%20Mark/Takai|title=US Representative K. Mark Takai (Democratic Party) \u2013 Billings Chamber Public Policy|work=billingschamber.com|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://publicservantsprayer.org/leaders/rep-mark-takai|title=Public Servants' Prayer|work=publicservantsprayer.org|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n|website     = {{url|marktakai.com}}\n|allegiance  = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch      = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears= 1999\u20132016\n|unit        = [[Hawaii Army National Guard]]<br />Charlie Company (Medical), 29th Brigade Support Battalion\n|battles     = [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]]\n|rank        = [[Lieutenant colonel]]\n|mawards = [[File:Meritorious Service ribbon.svg|border|23px]] [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]<br />[[File:Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|border|23px]] [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|U.S. Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br />[[File:Hawaii DSO.JPG|border|23px]] Hawaii Distinguished Service Order\n}}\n'''Kyle Mark Takai'''<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mark-takai-hawaii-democrat-serving-first-term-in-congress-dies-at-49/2016/07/20/58a131c8-4eb7-11e6-aa14-e0c1087f7583_story.html |title=Mark Takai, Hawaii Democrat serving first term in Congress, dies at 49 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=July 20, 2016 |access-date=July 22, 2016 |first=Emily |last=Langer }}</ref> (July 1, 1967&nbsp;\u2013 July 20, 2016) was an American politician from the state of [[Hawaii]] who served in the [[United States House of Representatives]], representing {{ushr|HI|1}}, from 2015 to 2016. He previously served in the [[Hawaii House of Representatives]] from 1994 to 2014.\n\nA native of [[Honolulu, Hawaii]], Takai last served in the [[Hawaii Army National Guard]] as a [[lieutenant colonel]] and took part in [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]] in 2009, concurrent to his political career. He became the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee for the U.S. House of Representatives in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Hawaii, 2014|2014 elections]], defeating former Congressman [[Charles Djou]] to win the seat. Takai announced in May 2016 that he would not seek re-election due to ill health; he died two months later.\n\n==Early life and education==\nTakai was born in Honolulu, Hawaii. He received his diploma from [[Pearl City High School (Hawaii)|Pearl City High School]] in 1985,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/hsta-and-nea-give-takai-huge-end-of-year-boost-with-endorsement/123 |title=HSTA and NEA Give Takai Huge End-of-Year Boost with Endorsement |work=Hawaii Reporter |date= |accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> where he was a four-time high school swimming champion and a high school All-American swimmer.<ref name=midweek>{{cite web|url=http://archives.midweek.com/content/columns/keepingscore_article/a_swim_star_turns_uh_watchdog/ |title=A Swim Star Turns UH Watchdog |publisher=MidWeek|date=June 13, 2007 |accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> Takai received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in Political Science and a [[Master of Public Health]] degree from the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]].<ref>{{cite news|first=K. Mark |last= Takai | work = Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2007/03/25/editorial/commentary3.html |title= Editorial: University View; Let\u2019s Give UH a Second Century of Promise |date=March 25, 2007|accessdate=July 23, 2016}}</ref> While at the university, Takai was a [[Western Athletic Conference]] champion swimmer, president of the Associated Students of the University of Hawaii, and editor-in-chief of the campus newspaper.<ref name=midweek/>\n\n==Political career==\nTakai was first elected to the [[Hawaii House of Representatives]] in 1994, representing the 34th house district of Pearl City, near [[Pearl Harbor]]. He won re-election eight more times before shifting to represent the 33rd house district of [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]] in 2012. Takai was Chairman of the House Committee on Culture and the Arts between 1997 and 2000. He also served as Vice Chairman of the House Committee on Higher Education (1995\u20132002) and as Chairman in 2003\u20132004. Additionally, he was the Chairman of the House Committee on Veterans, Military, & International Affairs, & Culture and the Arts.{{when|date=July 2016}} During the 2005 and 2006 sessions, Takai served as Vice Speaker of the House.<ref name=leg/>\n\nTakai left his 20-year tenure as a state representative to become the Democratic nominee for the [[United States House of Representatives]] for {{ushr|HI|1}} in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Hawaii, 2014|2014 elections]], following [[incumbent]] [[Colleen Hanabusa]]'s decision to run for the [[United States Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/23077766/state-rep-mark-takai-launches-congressional-bid |title=State Rep. Mark Takai launches congressional bid |publisher=Hawaii News Now |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=December 30, 2013}}</ref> He won the election with 51.2% of the vote, defeating Republican former Congressman [[Charles Djou]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Certified Election Results|url=http://elections.hawaii.gov/election-results/|website=Hawaii Office of Elections|publisher=State of Hawaii|accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> In November 2015, he introduced the Atomic Veterans Healthcare Parity Act, extending federal compensation to those made sick by involvement in cleanup operations after bomb tests on Pacific islands.<ref>{{cite news|title=Atomic veterans battle against illnesses and for recognition|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/today/index.ssf/2016/07/atomic_veterans_battle_against.html|accessdate=July 20, 2016|publisher=Oregon Live|first=Jennifer | last= LaFleur|date=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]<ref name=abc>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/freshman-hawaii-rep-mark-takai-dies-battle-cancer/story?id=40746773 |title=Freshman Hawaii Rep. Mark Takai Dies After Battle With Cancer |date=July 20, 2016 |access-date=July 22, 2016 |publisher=ABC News |first=Benjamin |last=Siegel }}</ref>\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces|Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]]\n*[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]<ref name=abc/>\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Contracting and Workforce|Subcommittee on Contracting and Workforce]] (Ranking Member)\n\n==Military service==\nTakai was commissioned as first lieutenant in the [[Hawaii Army National Guard]] (HIARNG) on July 19, 1999, and worked as the Preventive Medical Officer. He was the Division Chief for Soldiers Services and a School Liaison for the HIARNG. He later became a [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] on May 14, 2013. Additionally, Takai served as the President of the Hawaii National Guard Association and the President of the National Guard Association-Hawaii Insurance, Inc.<ref name=ltcol>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/state-rep-k-mark-takai-promoted-to-lieutenant-colonel/123 |title=State Rep. K. Mark Takai Promoted to Lieutenant Colonel |publisher=Hawaii Reporter |date=June 18, 2013 |accessdate=December 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTakai was called to active duty for six months (May to November 2005) and served as the Hawaii Army National Guard Deputy State Surgeon. He later served as the Company Commander of Charlie Company (Medical), 29th Brigade Support Battalion from November 2006 to May 2008. Takai was posted abroad during [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]] as the Base Operations Officer (Camp Mayor) at [[Kuwait Naval Base|Camp Patriot, Kuwait]], from February 2009 to September 2009.<ref name=leg>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/memberpage.aspx?member=takai|title=Legislative Members|publisher=Hawaii State Legislature|accessdate=July 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAmong his numerous awards and decorations, Takai received the Meritorious Service Medal from the United States Army in 2009,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kitv.com/story/32491122/congressman-mark-takai-dies-after-battle-with-pancreatic-cancer |title=Congressman Mark Takai dies after battle with pancreatic cancer |date=July 20, 2016 |access-date=July 22, 2016 |first=Moanike'ala |last=Nabarro |publisher=[[KITV]] }}</ref> the Distinguished Service Medal from the National Guard Association of the United States in 2011, and the Hawaii Distinguished Service Order in 2012.<ref name=ltcol/>\n\n==Illness and death==\nTakai was diagnosed with a [[pancreatic cancer|small tumor on his pancreas]] in late October 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blair|first1=Chad|title=Takai Has Small Tumor In Pancreas|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2015/10/takai-has-small-tumor-in-pancreas/|accessdate=July 23, 2016|work=Hawaii Civil Beat|date=October 27, 2015}}</ref> Takai announced on May 19, 2016, that he would not seek reelection because his cancer had spread, but vowed to serve out the remaining eight months of his term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/hawaiis-mark-takai-will-not-seek-re-election-pancreatic-cancer|title=Hawaii's Mark Takai Will Not Seek Re-Election|date=May 19, 2016|work=Roll Call|first= Simone | last = Path\u00e9 | accessdate=May 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/hawaii-congressman-mark-takai-retire-focus-cancer-battle-n577451|title=Hawaii Congressman Mark Takai to Retire to Focus on Cancer Battle|work=NBC News|date = May 20, 2016| accessdate=May 24, 2016 | first = Frances Kai-Hwa | last = Wang}}</ref> He died two months later at his home in [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]]. He was 49.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2016/07/us-rep-mark-takai-of-hawaii-dies/|title=US Rep. Mark Takai of Hawaii Dies|date=July 20, 2016|work= Honolulu Civil Beat | first = Chad | last = Blair | accessdate =July 20, 2016}}</ref> He was survived by his wife, Sami, and their two children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{CongBio|T000473}}\n*[http://www.marktakai.com Campaign site]\n*{{C-SPAN|Mark Takai}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| before = [[Colleen Hanabusa]]\n| years=2015\u20132016\n| state=Hawaii\n| district=1\n| after=Colleen Hanabusa}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Hawaii Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takai, Mark}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Hawaii House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States Congress of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:People from Honolulu]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii at Manoa alumni]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Rainbow Warriors swimmers]]\n[[Category:National Guard of the United States officers]]\n[[Category:Ameri